```csharp
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        int[] array = { 10, 80, 30, 90, 40, 50, 70 };
        QuickSort(array, 0, array.Length - 1);

        foreach (int num in array)
        {
            Console.Write(num + " ");
        }
    }

    static void QuickSort(int[] array, int low, int high)
    {
        if (low < high)
        {
            int pivotIndex = Partition(array, low, high);
            QuickSort(array, low, pivotIndex - 1);
            QuickSort(array, pivotIndex + 1, high);
        }
    }

    static int Partition(int[] array, int low, int high)
    {
        int pivot = array[high];
        int i = low - 1;

        for (int j = low; j < high; j++)
        {
            if (array[j] <= pivot)
            {
                i++;
                Swap(array, i, j);
            }
        }

        Swap(array, i + 1, high);
        return i + 1;
    }

    static void Swap(int[] array, int i, int j)
    {
        int temp = array[i];
        array[i] = array[j];
        array[j] = temp;
    }
}
```

This code defines a `QuickSort` method that recursively sorts the array by partitioning it around a pivot element. The `Partition` method is responsible for rearranging the elements and choosing the pivot. The `Swap` method is used to exchange elements within the array. The `Main` method demonstrates the usage of the quicksort algorithm by sorting an example array and printing the sorted array.

Designing a simple version control system from scratch would require implementing several functionalities, such as tracking file changes, saving different versions of files, and perhaps even branching and merging. Below is a basic prototype of such a system in C++, focusing primarily on tracking file changes and saving versions. This system will not include advanced features like branching and merging for simplicity.

The system will use a simple file structure to store versions and a text file to log changes. Each version of a file will be stored in a separate file within a directory designated for version control.

Please note, this example demonstrates basic concepts and doesn't cover many practical aspects such as error handling, efficiency, and security which are crucial for real-world applications.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <filesystem>
#include <sstream>

namespace fs = std::filesystem;

class SimpleVCS {
private:
    std::string workingDirectory;
    std::string vcsDirectory;
    std::string logFile;

    int getCurrentVersion(const std::string& filename) {
        std::ifstream log(this->logFile, std::ios::in);
        std::string line;
        int version = 0;
        while (std::getline(log, line)) {
            if (line.find(filename) != std::string::npos) {
                std::istringstream iss(line);
                std::string part;
                std::getline(iss, part, ':'); // Skip filename
                std::getline(iss, part, ':'); // Get version
                version = std::stoi(part);
            }
        }
        log.close();
        return version;
    }

public:
    SimpleVCS(const std::string& dir): workingDirectory(dir), vcsDirectory(dir + "/.simpleVCS"), logFile(vcsDirectory + "/log.txt") {
        fs::create_directories(this->vcsDirectory);
    }

    void trackFile(const std::string& filename) {
        int currentVersion = getCurrentVersion(filename);
        int newVersion = currentVersion + 1;

        // Copy file to version control system directory
        std::string versionedFilename = vcsDirectory + "/" + filename + "_" + std::to_string(newVersion);
        fs::copy(workingDirectory + "/" + filename, versionedFilename);

        // Log the new version
        std::ofstream log(this->logFile, std::ios::app);
        if (log.is_open()) {
            log << filename << ":" << newVersion << std::endl;
            log.close();
        } else {
            std::cerr << "Unable to open log file." << std::endl;
        }
    }

    void revertToVersion(const std::string& filename, int version) {
        std::string versionedFilename = vcsDirectory + "/" + filename + "_" + std::to_string(version);

        if (fs::exists(versionedFilename)) {
            // Replace the current file with the specified version
            fs::copy(versionedFilename, workingDirectory + "/" + filename, fs::copy_options::overwrite_existing);
        } else {
            std::cerr << "The specified version does not exist." << std::endl;
        }
    }
};

int main() {
    SimpleVCS vcs("/path/to/your/directory");

    // To track a new version of a file:
    vcs.trackFile("example.txt");

    // To revert to a specific version of a file:
    vcs.revertToVersion("example.txt", 1);

    return 0;
}
```

This code snippet demonstrates a fundamental approach to version control in C++. The `SimpleVCS` class allows you to track changes of any file and revert to any previous version by maintaining a simple log file. Modifications and enhancements can be added to scale the functionality, such as diffing files or handling binary files. 

The system assumes that the directory and file names do not contain spaces or special characters that could interfere with file operations. In a real-world application, these assumptions may not hold, and additional error handling and input sanitization might be necessary.

