To achieve what you're asking for using EPPlus, you need to read the excel table data row by row and then store each row into an instance of your `ExcelData` class, which should be added to a list. I'll guide you through the process. Before you begin, ensure you have the EPPlus package installed in your .NET project.

Here's how you can modify and expand upon your initial code to read the table and store its contents in a `List<ExcelData>`:

```csharp
using OfficeOpenXml;
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.IO;

public class ExcelData
{
    public string Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public string Gender { get; set; }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        var excelDataList = new List<ExcelData>();
        var fileInfo = new FileInfo(@"C:\ExcelFile.xlsx");

        using (var package = new ExcelPackage(fileInfo))
        {
            ExcelWorksheet worksheet = package.Workbook.Worksheets[0]; // Index is zero-based.
            var table = worksheet.Tables.First();

            // Assuming the first row is the header row and the following rows contain the data.
            for (int row = table.Address.Start.Row + 1; row <= table.Address.End.Row; row++)
            {
                var excelData = new ExcelData
                {
                    Id = worksheet.Cells[row, table.Columns["Id"].Position + 1].Text,
                    Name = worksheet.Cells[row, table.Columns["Name"].Position + 1].Text,
                    Gender = worksheet.Cells[row, table.Columns["Gender"].Position + 1].Text
                };

                excelDataList.Add(excelData);
            }
        }

        // Output to validate the data
        foreach (var data in excelDataList)
        {
            Console.WriteLine(data.Id + data.Name + data.Gender);
        }
    }
}
```

Important Notes:
- Ensure you have `using OfficeOpenXml;` at the top of your code file to reference the EPPlus library.
- The example assumes your Excel worksheet is the first worksheet in the workbook; adjust the worksheet index in `package.Workbook.Worksheets[0]` as necessary.
- The `for` loop starts at `table.Address.Start.Row + 1` to skip the header row and reads till `table.Address.End.Row`.
- Column positions are obtained using `table.Columns["ColumnName"].Position + 1`. EPPlus uses a 1-based index for rows/columns, but `Position` is 0-based, hence the `+ 1`.

